ping for is possible.\n\n- Patti\n|\nThey were steaming out of the station before Maia asked, 'Was it books in the trunk?''It was books, admitted Miss Minton.And Maia said, 'Good.\n\n- Eva Ibbotson, Journey to the River Sea\n|\nWhatever games are played with us, we must play no games with ourselves, but deal in our privacy with the last honesty and truth.\n\n- Ralph Waldo Emerson, The Essential Writings of Ralph Waldo Emerson\n|\nWhen I dare to be powerful, to use my strength in the service of my vision, then it becomes less and less important whether I am afraid.\n\n- Audre\n|\nTo realize one's destiny is a person's only real obligation and when you want something, all the universe conspires in helping you to achieve it.\n\n- Paulo Coelho, The Alchemist\n|\nI hope that someday when I am gone, someone, somewhere, picks my soul up off of these pages and thinks, 'I would have loved her.\n\n- Nicole\n|\nThink. In a minute from now you could be saying, I risked death. I threw for life, and I won life. It is a very wonderful feeling. To have survived.\n\n- John Fowles, The Magus\n|\nI swear to God . . .”“God doesn’t come to this part of the house, so swear to me.” -Liam C\n\n- J.J.\n|\nIn the frame of a known phenomenon of life, a human could be defined as the only proven thinking creature.\n\n- Eraldo\n|\nWhether your glass is half full or half empty, hope can fill it up.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nWar is not for winning, Masha,' sighed Koschei, reading the tracks of supply lines, of pincer strategies, over her shoulder. 'It is for surviving.\n\n- Catherynne M. Valente, Deathless\n|\nWhen the body escaped mutilation, seldom did the heart go to the grave unscarred.\n\n- Virginia Woolf, Jacob's Room\n|\nWords are life. They can tear down or build up, so use them wisely.\n\n- Mensah\n|\nI wait, you play. You speak, I cave. I promise, you break. You game me, daily, you play me.\n\n- Coco\n|\nWhat's the truth? The truth is what people WANT. Liars are basically idealists, liars are saints and prophets. Jesus was a liar.\n\n- Jane Rogers, Island\n|\nIt was a wonderful life. To have a stage play right in this room, with real people acting real parts.\n\n- Jan Karon, Home to Holly Springs\n|\nDon't think of introversion as something that needs to be cured...Spend your free the way you like, not the way you think you're supposed to.\n\n- Susan Cain, Quiet: The Power of Introverts in a World That Can't Stop Talking"